<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="52" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="13.[140,1108,1011,1671]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,320,1328,1354]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[185,315,1328,1354]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" reason="1">Etymology</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the shape of surstylus in male genitalia, which presents the distal margin divided in two lobules posteriorly (see 
<figureCitation box="[951,1045,1363,1390]" captionStart="Figure 44" captionStartId="21.[140,212,1107,1129]" captionTargetBox="[278,976,186,1082]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[270,980,165,1089]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 44. Eosphaerophoria bifida, male genitalia: a left lateral view b right superior lobe, dorsal view c tergite 9, cerci and surstyli, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767594/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">Fig. 44c</figureCitation>
), and it is from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[355,428,1399,1425]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">bifidus</emphasis>
meaning split into two parts, bifurcated (
<bibRefCitation author="Brown RW" box="[891,1095,1398,1425]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" refId="ref18587" refString="Brown RW (1956) Composition of scientific words, a manual of methods and a lexicon of materials for the practice of logotechnics. Published by the author, Baltimore, 882 pp." type="book" year="1956">Brown 1956: 345</bibRefCitation>
). Species epithet to be treated as adjective.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="52" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="13.[140,1108,1011,1671]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,451,1469,1495]" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis box="[185,324,1469,1495]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" reason="1">Differential</emphasis>
diagnosis.
</emphasis>
Species easy to identify by an elongated yellow macula on 2nd abdominal tergum and the face entirely yellow. It has the male genitalia similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[140,306,1539,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteofasciata">
<emphasis box="[140,306,1539,1565]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">E. luteofasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, especially the bifurcated surstylus. The surstylus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[913,1010,1539,1565]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[913,1010,1539,1565]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two lobes of different sizes (
<figureCitation box="[406,559,1575,1601]" captionStart="Figure 44" captionStartId="21.[140,212,1107,1129]" captionTargetBox="[278,976,186,1082]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[270,980,165,1089]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figure 44. Eosphaerophoria bifida, male genitalia: a left lateral view b right superior lobe, dorsal view c tergite 9, cerci and surstyli, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767594" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767594/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">Figs 44a, 44c</figureCitation>
) but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[623,788,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteofasciata">
<emphasis box="[623,788,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">E. luteofasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the surstylus divided in two similar lobes in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[508,665,1610,1637]" captionStart="Figure 47" captionStartId="27.[140,212,1136,1158]" captionTargetBox="[296,952,178,1106]" captionTargetId="figure@27.[289,958,165,1116]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="Figure 47. Eosphaerophoria luteofasciata, male genitalia a left lateral view b right basal appendix of aedeagus c right superior lobe, dorsal view d tergite 9, cerci and surstyli, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3767600" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3767600/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">Figs 47a, 47d</figureCitation>
). Moreover, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[806,901,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[806,901,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has superior lobes with conical shape and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[405,569,1645,1671]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteofasciata">
<emphasis box="[405,569,1645,1671]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="52">E. luteofasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has them expanded anteroventrally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="14.[140,1108,167,651]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[185,298,167,193]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis box="[185,293,167,193]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" reason="1">Remarks</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[308,561,167,193]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[308,561,167,193]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Eosphaerophoria bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described based on a single male from Wau (
<collectingCountry box="[147,375,202,229]" name="Papua New Guinea" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Papua New Guinea</collectingCountry>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[395,645,202,228]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[395,645,202,228]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Eosphaerophoria bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
could be the male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[895,1054,203,228]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[895,1054,203,228]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is described from two females, 
<typeStatus box="[489,588,237,263]" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">holotype</typeStatus>
also from Wau. There are differences between both species. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[297,395,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[297,395,272,298]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an all yellow face, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[716,877,273,298]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[716,877,273,298]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a medial broad black facial vitta. However, this character does show dimorphic variation (for example see 
<taxonomicName box="[180,325,343,368]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis box="[180,325,343,368]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), but in this case is much more divergent. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[813,1064,343,369]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[813,1064,343,369]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">Eosphaerophoria bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a yellow macula on 2nd tergum and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[550,708,379,404]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[550,708,379,404]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
does not or it is not clear (see comments about variation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[425,583,414,439]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[425,583,414,439]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). In species with both sexes known, such as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="marginata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. marginata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[310,478,449,474]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vietnamensis">
<emphasis box="[310,478,449,474]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. vietnamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the abdominal pattern does not display significant differences. The fact that both species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[548,644,483,509]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[548,644,483,509]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[701,859,484,509]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[701,859,484,509]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were collected in the same region but in different years is not an argument to consider them the same taxon, because there is an example of different species collected from the same place and the same date, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[265,434,590,615]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vietnamensis">
<emphasis box="[265,434,590,615]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. vietnamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[490,643,590,615]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="symmetrica">
<emphasis box="[490,643,590,615]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. symmetrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on this, we consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[963,1058,589,615]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis box="[963,1058,589,615]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mengual &amp; Ghorpadé" authorityYear="2010" box="[140,298,625,650]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Eosphaerophoria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrovittata">
<emphasis box="[140,298,625,650]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="53">E. nigrovittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as being different species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
